defaultUK Green Building Coun
defaultcil (UK-GBC) is an independent, 
defaultmem
defaultbership-based
default 
defaultcharity
default committed to radically improving the sustainabil
defaultity of the built environment by 
defaulttransforming the way it is planned, designed, constr
defaultucted, maintained and operated. We have around 400 members from across the property and construction sector, including house builders, local authorities, Registered Providers and product manufacturers. UK-GBC was on the steering group for the Housing Standards Review technical committee.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is UK-GBC’s view that the time was right for a review and rationalisation of 
defaultthe current range of voluntary standards applied to new homes. 
defaultHowever, we have always maintained that the changes must support deliver
defaulty of 
defaulthigh quality sustainability homes 
defaultthat are 
defaultfit for the future. W
defaultith the demise of the CSH and 
defaultomissions 
defaultin the Housing Standards Review consultation 
defaultaround issues like materials, we risk losing a momentum that has transformed the way homes have been built over the last seven years.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultUK-GBC 
defaultagrees 
defaultthat where appropriate, standards should be brought into Building Regulations
default. However, we believe that this process should happen
default as soon as possible, and we do not believe that th
defaulte government's self imposed 'o
defaultne in two out' rule is a valid excuse to delay action.
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne of the key functions of the CSH was to set out the direction of travel for Building Regulations. In our view it has been helpful to have a sense of what best practice looks like that developers can and should aspire to, and in the absence of the CSH the onus will be on the industry to drive innovation and best practice. Some developers have embraced sustainability and are innovating and achieving impressive sustainability standards. For them, there are elements of the CSH that were deeply frustrating, because inevitably the CSH is prescriptive. However, the industry has a ‘long tail’, with many companies who are either not interested in sustainability, or not able to carry out the necessary research and development to innovate. We need a new kind of 
defaultsustainability framework which allows the leaders to keep pushing the boundaries, but also provides the guidance and drivers to act for the rest of the industry. 
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe believe that suitable transitional arrangements must be put into place, and where 
defaultLocal Planning Authorities (
defaultLPAs
default)
default already have higher standards in place 
defaultwhich have been tested through due process and accepted as viable, 
defaultthey should be allowed to keep those higher requirements until the new regulations take over (e
default.
defaultg
default.
default Part L 2016). There is no sense in weakening requirements which are
default already
default being met, only to raise them again in 2-3 years.  
