default&#xa0;default4.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIndoordefault Environmental Standardsdefault4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe agree with the Challenge Panel's assertion that standards for daylight, sunlight and ventilation should be more thoroughly investigated.
default 
defaultDaylighting, sunlight and ventilation are all intertwined and must be considered as a whole. The tools for assessing these matters should also be reviewed. 
default 
default&#xa0;default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLinked to the above, the issue of overheating is a real concern as new homes become more airtight. The government’s response to the issue has so far been inadequate, despite the fact that private sector guidance exists on this issue - for example
default CIBSE Guide TM52 sets overheating standards. 
defaultUK-GBC believes that 
defaultSAP should
default be improved to better
default address this issue as a matter of urgency
default – as recommended by the Zero Carbon Hub
default 3 years ago.
default&#xa0;
default5.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWaterdefault5.1default&#xa0; 
defaultSince the upper standard of 105 l/p/d + 5l external use is achievable at no/minimal extra cost, we think this should be the baseline standard for all new homes. Our members are meeting this standard on new homes as a matter of course, at no extra cost.
default Code level 5 (80 l/p/d) is usually not viable, apart from in exceptional circumstances. 
defaultIn future there could be scope for 'allowable solutions' type approaches for water, but that approach would need to be developed at a national level.
default&#xa0;default6.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMaterialsdefault6.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe st
defaultrongly disagree with leaving considerations about m
defaultaterials to the market
default. While we recognise that EU policy is beginning to address these issues through standards like CEN TC350, we still feel that there’s a need for national driver to encourage the procurement of healthier and more sustainable construction materials
default. This is perhaps the biggest omission in the proposed new Housing Standards.
default&#xa0;
default6.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIssue
defaults such as
default responsible sourcing, toxicity, Ozone depleting potential, and off-gassing of materials in air-tight homes should be addressed as a matter of urgency through new guidance and
default through Building R
defaultegulation
defaults
default.
